{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_12","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"cat /nvidia-kaggle/skills/nvidia-kaggle-skill/kernels.md\npython - <<'PY'\nimport json, pathlib\nout=pathlib.Path('/nvidia-kaggle/demo/competition-intel-briefing/runs/codex_rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction_017')\nfor name in ['kernels_query.json','discussions_query.json']:\n    print('\\\\n###', name)\n    data=json.loads((out/name).read_text() or '[]')\n    print(type(data), len(data) if isinstance(data, list) else data.keys())\n    rows=data if isinstance(data,list) else data.get('items') or data.get('rows') or []\n    for r in rows[:10]:\n        print(r)\nPY\"","aggregated_output":"# Kaggle Kernels\n\nUse this workflow to fetch, browse, and research Kaggle competition kernels/notebooks.\n\n## Inputs\n\n| Input | Required | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| `competition_id` | Yes for ingest/query/research | Kaggle competition slug. |\n| `kernel_ref` | Yes for read | Kaggle kernel reference such as `owner/kernel-slug` or a Kaggle code URL. |\n| `KAGGLE_API_TOKEN` | Yes | KGAT token string for Kaggle APIs and SDK search. |\n| Optional filters | No | Search, author, vote threshold, sorting, limits, raw output, and refresh flags. |\n\n## Core Commands\n\n```bash\npython ./scripts/kernel_ingest.py <competition_id> [--max-pages N] [--sort-by FIELD] [--page-size N]\npython ./scripts/kernel_query.py <competition_id> [--search TERM] [--min-votes N] [--author NAME] [--limit N] [--as-json]\npython ./scripts/kernel_read.py <kernel_ref> [--competition-id ID] [--raw] [--force]\npython ./scripts/kernel_db_info.py [competition_id]\n```\n\nSort options for ingest are `hotness`, `dateCreated`, `dateRun`, and `voteCount`.\n\n## Top Kernel And Lineage Research\n\nUse this when the user asks for top kernels, leaderboard notebook research, public score verification, or how public notebooks build on each other.\n\nProgress checklist:\n\n```text\n- [ ] Phase 1: Collect leaderboard and kernel lists\n- [ ] Phase 2: Pull kernel metadata and code for top kernels\n- [ ] Phase 3: Build dependency graph from metadata and code refs\n- [ ] Phase 4: Write report\n```\n\nFetch public kernel scores:\n\n```bash\npython ./scripts/fetch_top_kernel_scores.py <competition_id> --sort descending\npython ./scripts/fetch_top_kernel_scores.py <competition_id> --sort ascending\npython ./scripts/fetch_kernel_score.py <owner/kernel-slug>\n```\n\nThe top-score script first enumerates competition-scoped kernels through the Kaggle API, then enriches exact `owner/slug` refs with SDK score data. Do not use broad SDK search results as the source of truth for which kernels belong to a competition.\n\nCollect leaderboard and source evidence:\n\n```bash\nkaggle kernels list --competition <competition_id> --sort-by voteCount --page-size 40 -v\nkaggle competitions leaderboard <competition_id> --show -v\nmkdir -p /tmp/kernel_research/<short-name>\ncd /tmp/kernel_research/<short-name>\nkaggle kernels pull <owner/slug> -m\n```\n\nExtract evidence from `kernel-metadata.json` (`kernel_sources`, `dataset_sources`) and notebook/script source (Kaggle URLs, credit strings, `/kaggle/input/` references, author mentions).\n\nWrite `top_kernels_research.md` unless the user requests another path. Include leaderboard snapshot, verified public scores, lineage chains with `[metadata]` or `[code ref]` labels, observed techniques, open questions, and links.\n\n## Storage\n\n| Path | Contents |\n|---|---|\n| `data/kernels.db` | SQLite kernel metadata and competition info |\n| `data/notebooks/<comp>/<ref>/` | Cached notebooks and `kernel-metadata.json` |\n| `top_kernels_research.md` | Optional top-kernel and lineage report |\n| `/tmp/kernel_research/<short-name>` | Temporary pulled kernel evidence |\n\n## Workflow-Specific Troubleshooting\n\nSee [SKILL.md](SKILL.md#troubleshooting) for common credential, access, cache, and rate-limit failures.\n\n| Symptom | Action |\n|---|---|\n| SDK score search omits a score | Keep the kernel row and label the score as missing. |\n\n### kernels_query.json\n<class 'list'> 30\n{'competition_id': 'rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction', 'ref': 'nihilisticneuralnet/9-251-rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction-dwt-based', 'title': '9.251 ROGII-Wellbore Geology Prediction: DWT-based', 'author': 'parthenos', 'total_votes': 588, 'last_run_time': '2026-05-13T06:31:11.020000Z', 'is_private': False, 'ingested_at': '2026-06-13T07:40:09.648697Z'}\n{'competition_id': 'rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction', 'ref': 'ravaghi/wellbore-geology-prediction-ridge', 'title': 'Wellbore Geology Prediction | Ridge', 'author': 'Mahdi Ravaghi', 'total_votes': 227, 'last_run_time': '2026-06-06T02:07:29.667000Z', 'is_private': False, 'ingested_at': '2026-06-13T07:40:09.648723Z'}\n{'competition_id': 'rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction', 'ref': 'ravaghi/wellbore-geology-prediction-hill-climbing', 'title': 'Wellbore Geology Prediction | Hill Climbing', 'author': 'Mahdi Ravaghi', 'total_votes': 195, 'last_run_time': '2026-06-08T10:57:32.340000Z', 'is_private': False, 'ingested_at': '2026-06-13T07:40:09.648735Z'}\n{'competition_id': 'rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction', 'ref': 'pixiux/rogii-dual-pipeline-blend', 'title': 'rogii_dual_pipeline_blend', 'author': 'PyJa', 'total_votes': 195, 'last_run_time': '2026-06-10T11:24:57.013000Z', 'is_private': False, 'ingested_at': '2026-06-13T07:40:09.648730Z'}\n{'competition_id': 'rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction', 'ref': 'romantamrazov/rogii-super-solution-lb-top-3', 'title': '[ROGII] SUPER SOLUTION |LB: TOP 3 ', 'author': 'Roman Tamrazov', 'total_votes': 169, 'last_run_time': '2026-05-08T08:57:56.697000Z', 'is_private': False, 'ingested_at': '2026-06-13T07:40:09.648740Z'}\n{'competition_id': 'rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction', 'ref': 'nina2025/rogii-h-blend-v1', 'title': 'ROGII |🐼 h-blend v1', 'author': 'f.a.nina', 'total_votes': 164, 'last_run_time': '2026-05-16T18:57:54.677000Z', 'is_private': False, 'ingested_at': '2026-06-13T07:40:09.648746Z'}\n{'competition_id': 'rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction', 'ref': 'cdeotte/xgb-starter-cv-15', 'title': 'XGB Starter - [CV 15]', 'author': 'Chris Deotte', 'total_votes': 159, 'last_run_time': '2026-05-06T03:21:07.053000Z', 'is_private': False, 'ingested_at': '2026-06-13T07:40:09.648751Z'}\n{'competition_id': 'rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction', 'ref': 'pilkwang/rogii-eda-target-free-alignment-for-tvt', 'title': '🛢️ ROGII EDA + Target-Free Alignment for TVT', 'author': 'Pilkwang Kim', 'total_votes': 150, 'last_run_time': '2026-06-05T12:30:39.217000Z', 'is_private': False, 'ingested_at': '2026-06-13T07:40:09.648762Z'}\n{'competition_id': 'rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction', 'ref': 'jaemin3404/rogii-sp45-fleongg-blend-v2', 'title': 'rogii-sp45-fleongg-blend-v2', 'author': 'JAEMIN', 'total_votes': 148, 'last_run_time': '2026-06-08T15:56:24.870000Z', 'is_private': False, 'ingested_at': '2026-06-13T07:40:09.648767Z'}\n{'competition_id': 'rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction', 'ref': 'ravaghi/wellbore-geology-prediction-lightgbm', 'title': 'Wellbore Geology Prediction | LightGBM', 'author': 'Mahdi Ravaghi', 'total_votes': 147, 'last_run_time': '2026-06-08T10:57:22.413000Z', 'is_private': False, 'ingested_at': '2026-06-13T07:40:09.648772Z'}\n\n### discussions_query.json\n<class 'list'> 30\n{'competition_id': 'rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction', 'discussion_id': 697418, 'title': 'Diagram of the problem', 'author': 'Zacchaeus', 'author_username': 'zacchaeus', 'author_tier': 'MASTER', 'votes': 127, 'comment_count': 9, 'body_markdown': '![](https://www.googleapis.com/download/storage/v1/b/kaggle-forum-message-attachments/o/inbox%2F4080021%2F3f56527c733365a94d929bdc0600c7ef%2Fig_023b4ba06ac0441e0169fa9248ca54819aacb93888a02601a8.png?generation=1778029361497538&alt=media)', 'url': 'https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discussion/697418', 'tags': [], 'created_at': '2026-05-06T01:02:47.450389300Z', 'updated_at': '2026-06-09T21:01:13.203333300Z', 'last_fetched_at': '2026-06-13T07:59:41.296942+00:00', 'ingested_at': '2026-06-13T07:59:40.892031Z'}\n{'competition_id': 'rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction', 'discussion_id': 698825, 'title': 'How Geologists Interpret Wells: Some Helpful Tips', 'author': 'Igor Kuvaev', 'author_username': 'igorakuvaev', 'author_tier': 'CONTRIBUTOR', 'votes': 51, 'comment_count': 3, 'body_markdown': 'Kagglers, \\nyou are doing great so far, and we are excited to see the improving RMSE on the leaderboard.\\nIn the comments on this post, I will share some helpful tricks that geologists use to come up with the best interpretations.', 'url': 'https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discussion/698825', 'tags': [], 'created_at': '2026-05-11T18:36:29.863271400Z', 'updated_at': '2026-05-11T19:36:50.590Z', 'last_fetched_at': '2026-06-13T07:59:41.296942+00:00', 'ingested_at': '2026-06-13T07:59:40.892064Z'}\n{'competition_id': 'rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction', 'discussion_id': 697406, 'title': 'Geological Formations on well Geology (region: Texas)', 'author': 'Marília Prata', 'author_username': 'mpwolke', 'author_tier': 'GRANDMASTER', 'votes': 49, 'comment_count': 2, 'body_markdown': '## Geological Formations\\n\\nANCC, ASTNU, ASTNL, EGFDU, EGFDL, BUDA - Predicted depth of various geological formations (Training only). And Categorical labels indicating the geological unit in Geology column (train typewells)\\n\\n### BUDA Limestone\\n\\n\"The Buda Limestone is a dense white to yellow sparry limestone with numerous calcite veins that weathers to yellowish or pinkish due to its iron content.\"\\n\\nCoordinates\\t30.0849°N 97.8507°W - Region: North America\\n\\nhttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buda_Limestone\\n\\n### ANCC - Anacacho Limestone\\n\\n\"The Anacacho Limestone is a unit of limestone of Cretaceous (Campanian) age in Texas. Most of the Anacacho Limestone is interpreted as having accumulated in relatively shallow (<50 m depth) marine water.\"\\n\\nhttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anacacho_Limestone\\n\\n\\n### ASTNU and ASTNL \\n\\nAustin Chalk (U = **Upper Austin Chalk**, L = **Lower Austin Chalk**).\\n\\n\"The Austin Chalk is an upper Cretaceous geologic formation in the Gulf Coast region of the United States.\"\\n\\n\"The rocks of the Austin Chalk consist of recrystallized, fossiliferous, interbedded chalks and marls. Exposures of Austin Chalk are mainly seen in quarries, roadcuts, and stream beds where water eroded the soil. \"\\n\\nhttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Austin_Chalk\\n\\n### EFGDU and EFGDL  \\n\\nEagle Ford (U = **Upper Eagle Ford**, L = **Lower Eagle Ford**).\\n\\n\"The **Eagle Ford Group** (also called the Eagle Ford Shale) is a sedimentary rock formation deposited during the Cenomanian and Turonian ages of the Late Cretaceous over much of the modern-day state of Texas. The Eagle Ford is predominantly composed of organic matter-rich fossiliferous marine shales and marls with interbedded thin limestones.\"\\n\\nhttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eagle_Ford_Group\\n\\n### Olmos\\n\\n\"The Olmos Formation is a Late Cretaceous formation in the easternmost portion of the Rio Grande Embayment of the Gulf Coast Basin in Texas. It is the uppermost unit in the Campanian Taylor Group of Texas, unconformably overlain by the Escondido Formation and underlain by San Miguel Formation . Both of the Escondido and San Miguel Formations are sequences of mudstone and sandstone.\"\\n\\nhttps://gccc.beg.utexas.edu/co2-data/olmos-00', 'url': 'https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discussion/697406', 'tags': [], 'created_at': '2026-05-05T23:00:26.955260900Z', 'updated_at': '2026-05-15T02:18:26.703333300Z', 'last_fetched_at': '2026-06-13T07:59:41.296942+00:00', 'ingested_at': '2026-06-13T07:59:40.892075Z'}\n{'competition_id': 'rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction', 'discussion_id': 699853, 'title': 'multi-trajectory prediction (MTP) with deep CNN for welllog inversion', 'author': 'hengck23', 'author_username': 'hengck23', 'author_tier': 'GRANDMASTER', 'votes': 47, 'comment_count': 92, 'body_markdown': 'example notebook\\nhttps://www.kaggle.com/code/hengck23/cnn-mtp-example?scriptVersionId=320093395\\n\\narvix paper: \"Direct Multi-Modal Inversion of Geophysical Logs Using Deep Learning\" - Sergey Alyaev  \\nhttps://arxiv.org/pdf/2201.01871\\nhttps://nfes.org/assets/workshop2022/ambrus_sequential_multi_mode_inversion_poster.pdf\\n\\n```\\n[2D Heatmap Input] ──> [Regression Head (CNN)] ──> [MDN Predictor (MLP)] ──> [Multi-Trajectory Output]\\n\\nexample of heatmap is shown below.\\nThe Mixture Density Network (MDN) Predictor : for multiple paths hypothesis (like k-beam).\\n\\nif you can identify match keypoints in GR signals, then you decide how to move/traverse between the matched keypoints.\\n```\\n\\n\\n![](https://www.googleapis.com/download/storage/v1/b/kaggle-forum-message-attachments/o/inbox%2F113660%2F7482e84e8978ff732cdcc907d6f9d684%2FSelection_3550.png?generation=1778852910817071&alt=media)\\n\\n![](https://www.googleapis.com/download/storage/v1/b/kaggle-forum-message-attachments/o/inbox%2F113660%2F6c2c44a7ecf5436b444bd418ea7b96bb%2FSelection_3551.png?generation=1778852946405152&alt=media)\\n\\n![](https://www.googleapis.com/download/storage/v1/b/kaggle-forum-message-attachments/o/inbox%2F113660%2F2d908d758ec3e6c9b53ef3ea87db67f4%2FSelection_3552.png?generation=1778852956595369&alt=media)\\n\\n', 'url': 'https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discussion/699853', 'tags': [], 'created_at': '2026-05-15T13:49:18.283461700Z', 'updated_at': '2026-06-08T10:14:32.910Z', 'last_fetched_at': '2026-06-13T07:59:41.296942+00:00', 'ingested_at': '2026-06-13T07:59:40.892084Z'}\n{'competition_id': 'rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction', 'discussion_id': 700424, 'title': 'Share an UI visualizer ', 'author': 'Tom', 'author_username': 'tom99763', 'author_tier': 'MASTER', 'votes': 46, 'comment_count': 60, 'body_markdown': '![](https://www.googleapis.com/download/storage/v1/b/kaggle-forum-message-attachments/o/inbox%2F4310004%2F8fe8f43532b152aa5a7637b7d6f1a2fe%2FUI1.png?generation=1779022020724846&alt=media)\\n\\nFeel free to use it: https://github.com/tom99763/rogii-viewer  \\n\\nAnd some EDA & directions in attachments. I suggest people to read `glossary.html` first to clarify some confused definition. \\n\\nI really like this explaination about TVT:\\n\\n```\\nAnalogy: TVT is the “floor number” in a geological building\\n\\nImagine the geology as a completed high-rise building, where each floor represents a different rock layer (ANCC, Austin Chalk, Eagle Ford, Buda, etc.).\\n\\nTypewell = the elevator shaft: it goes vertically from the top floor to the basement, recording “the GR at this layer is X” as it passes through each floor.\\nHorizontal well = a person walking inside the building:  moving along the hallway of a certain floor, sometimes going up or down between floors.\\nTVT = which floor is this person currently on?\\n```\\n\\n### Update GR Mismatch Visualizer\\n\\n![](https://www.googleapis.com/download/storage/v1/b/kaggle-forum-message-attachments/o/inbox%2F4310004%2F5b91ffbfc5d669a76d10fe1cb409dcb5%2FGR.png?generation=1779030611267623&alt=media)', 'url': 'https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discussion/700424', 'tags': [], 'created_at': '2026-05-17T12:47:20.845780400Z', 'updated_at': '2026-06-13T03:26:44.953333300Z', 'last_fetched_at': '2026-06-13T07:59:41.296942+00:00', 'ingested_at': '2026-06-13T07:59:40.892097Z'}\n{'competition_id': 'rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction', 'discussion_id': 697431, 'title': 'besides regression, also dwt (time warping)! ', 'author': 'hengck23', 'author_username': 'hengck23', 'author_tier': 'GRANDMASTER', 'votes': 34, 'comment_count': 36, 'body_markdown': 'related to geosteering. Here, given a strip of MD-GR of the horizontal well, \"stretch and fold\" it so that it matches the TVT-GR reference of the typewell\\n\\n\\n![](https://www.googleapis.com/download/storage/v1/b/kaggle-forum-message-attachments/o/inbox%2F113660%2Fb40517687f05f7ecea819763d3b150dc%2FSelection_3412.png?generation=1778261192499811&alt=media)\\n\\n![](https://www.googleapis.com/download/storage/v1/b/kaggle-forum-message-attachments/o/inbox%2F113660%2F6f36c16fad39781039af137e753996dd%2FSelection_3304.png?generation=1778038684983121&alt=media)\\n\\n\\n---\\n\\nbut, since the test and train locations are pretty close, pure regression might just also work\\n', 'url': 'https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discussion/697431', 'tags': [], 'created_at': '2026-05-06T03:38:07.141461Z', 'updated_at': '2026-05-26T15:42:49.200Z', 'last_fetched_at': '2026-06-13T07:59:41.296942+00:00', 'ingested_at': '2026-06-13T07:59:40.892106Z'}\n{'competition_id': 'rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction', 'discussion_id': 697416, 'title': 'Welcome to ROGII - Wellbore Geology Prediction!', 'author': 'Igor Kuvaev', 'author_username': 'igorakuvaev', 'author_tier': 'CONTRIBUTOR', 'votes': 28, 'comment_count': 14, 'body_markdown': 'We (ROGII) are excited to welcome you to this challenge.\\n\\nThe presented dataset is a very typical example of modern horizontal drilling data. It contains the well trajectory along with Gamma Ray (GR) measurements collected along the wellbore. This dataset can be confidently interpreted by an experienced human interpreter.\\n\\nWe look forward to the results of this competition, as they may help enable automation during the well drilling process.\\n\\nWe strongly encourage you to **review the PowerPoint presentation attached to the competition data**, as it contains key information on horizontal well interpretation.\\n\\nAdditionally, feel free to watch how the manual geosteering process works:\\nhttps://youtu.be/VgzFt7xknGo?si=LfqTlmjsZpNmtbJH&t=1034\\n\\nMost importantly, make sure you enjoy the competition. You are solving a real-world problem, and successful solutions will be greatly appreciated by the industry by making drilling safer, more efficient, and lower in emissions.\\n\\nIf you have any questions, we would be happy to address them.\\n\\n— On behalf of all organizers,\\nROGII\\n', 'url': 'https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discussion/697416', 'tags': [], 'created_at': '2026-05-06T00:04:21.663312300Z', 'updated_at': '2026-06-09T21:57:50.866666700Z', 'last_fetched_at': '2026-06-13T07:59:41.296942+00:00', 'ingested_at': '2026-06-13T07:59:40.892114Z'}\n{'competition_id': 'rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction', 'discussion_id': 699289, 'title': 'Paradigm Shift: Why pure Tabular Models might be hitting a wall (Spatial & Sequential Context)', 'author': 'Amged Alfaqih', 'author_username': 'AmgedAlfaqih', 'author_tier': 'CONTRIBUTOR', 'votes': 21, 'comment_count': 4, 'body_markdown': '**Hi everyone,**\\n\\nAfter spending some time diving deep into the data and experimenting with various preprocessing pipelines, I noticed a common trap we might all be falling into: treating this purely as a standard tabular regression problem.\\n\\nIf you are just passing [X, Y, Z, MD, GR] into LightGBM or XGBoost, you will eventually hit a hard ceiling on your CV/LB score. Why? Because the models are missing the physical and spatial realities of the wellbore trajectory.\\n\\n## **1. The Sequential Reality (Physics of the Drill)**\\n\\nWe aren\\'t just looking at random rows; we are tracing a path. Features like MD (Measured Depth) and Z dictate a trajectory.\\n\\nInstead of simple lags and rolling windows, has anyone experimented with Particle Filters (PF) or Beam Search? By treating the expected TVT as a moving particle that updates its state based on the Gamma Ray (GR) observations and spatial constraints, we can create incredibly strong baseline predictions to feed into our Gradient Boosting models.\\n\\n## **2. The Spatial Reality (Geology is Continuous)**\\n\\nA well doesn\\'t exist in a vacuum; it shares the same geological formation as its neighbors.\\n\\nRelying solely on X and Y coordinates in a tree model is inefficient. A better approach is using Spatial Imputation (like cKDTree) to find the nearest known wells and calculate the median TVT or formation depth in that specific localized area.\\n\\nFeeding this \"spatial neighborhood consensus\" as a feature massively stabilizes the predictions for unseen evaluation rows.\\n\\nBy shifting the focus from \"tuning model hyperparameters\" to \"building physics-aware and spatial-aware features\", the performance jump is massive.\\n\\nAre you guys currently using any sequential tracking (like Particle Filters/Kalman Filters) or mostly relying on heavy rolling/lag statistical features?\\n\\nWould love to hear your thoughts!\\n\\n', 'url': 'https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discussion/699289', 'tags': [], 'created_at': '2026-05-13T12:22:48.528355700Z', 'updated_at': '2026-05-16T18:59:08.736666700Z', 'last_fetched_at': '2026-06-13T07:59:41.296942+00:00', 'ingested_at': '2026-06-13T07:59:40.892122Z'}\n{'competition_id': 'rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction', 'discussion_id': 698449, 'title': 'Duplicate type wells for different horizontal wells', 'author': 'RMorrison', 'author_username': 'rmorrison0', 'author_tier': 'CONTRIBUTOR', 'votes': 19, 'comment_count': 3, 'body_markdown': \"When doing a quick EDA, I noticed there are a few type well files that are exactly the same but assigned to different horizontal wells. In some cases this makes sense (wells that are oriented adjacent or on top of each other), but in other cases the wells are quite distant from each other. Why would wells some distance apart be using exactly the same type well? Is this intentional?\\n\\nHere are the well pairs with matching type wells, and a picture of how they are oriented compared to other wells with different type wells.\\n\\nduplicate_groups = [\\n    ['02e7fe5a', '10b89021', '3417285d', '6ae68655', '7993a768', 'bc4381e2', 'ecdab904', 'f021b650', 'f49fdea3', 'f88ddb26'],\\n    ['071d7b45', '4463446c'],\\n    ['25939962', '8050c789'],\\n    ['2f8e53c3', '91db7070'],\\n    ['75cd5f11', 'be83e781'],\\n    ['7b38844c', 'ed6e6e54'],\\n    ['89f1085d', 'aed44918'],\\n    ['8b95d6d1', 'a2e8e7f6'],\\n    ['a4f989c2', 'd011f41b'],\\n    ['add9c322', 'cbe62450'],\\n    ['b977be4a', 'c908edd0'],\\n    ['cd7f1687', 'fcfcc902'],\\n    ['f321a31c', 'fa667be2'],\\n]\\n\\n\", 'url': 'https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discussion/698449', 'tags': [], 'created_at': '2026-05-09T23:30:08.615841200Z', 'updated_at': '2026-05-10T15:45:31.636666700Z', 'last_fetched_at': '2026-06-13T07:59:41.296942+00:00', 'ingested_at': '2026-06-13T07:59:40.892133Z'}\n{'competition_id': 'rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction', 'discussion_id': 699326, 'title': 'stage.1 : global search using linear prior tvt = linear(md,z)', 'author': 'hengck23', 'author_username': 'hengck23', 'author_tier': 'GRANDMASTER', 'votes': 18, 'comment_count': 5, 'body_markdown': '![](https://www.googleapis.com/download/storage/v1/b/kaggle-forum-message-attachments/o/inbox%2F113660%2F1aabc18ee91163e6ba228c5e1db9b147%2FSelection_3505.png?generation=1778687376098048&alt=media)\\n\\nNext post: stage.2 iterative local search for refinement ', 'url': 'https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discussion/699326', 'tags': [], 'created_at': '2026-05-13T15:49:38.319727500Z', 'updated_at': '2026-06-03T01:37:42.410Z', 'last_fetched_at': '2026-06-13T07:59:41.296942+00:00', 'ingested_at': '2026-06-13T07:59:40.892144Z'}\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
