e might all be falling\n11:into: treating this purely as a standard tabular regression problem.            \n12-\n13:If you are just passing [X, Y, Z, MD, GR] into LightGBM or XGBoost, you will    \n14:eventually hit a hard ceiling on your CV/LB score. Why? Because the models are  \n15:missing the physical and spatial realities of the wellbore trajectory.          \n16-\n--\n20-We aren't just looking at random rows; we are tracing a path. Features like MD  \n21:(Measured Depth) and Z dictate a trajectory.                                    \n22-\n23-Instead of simple lags and rolling windows, has anyone experimented with        \n24:Particle Filters (PF) or Beam Search? By treating the expected TVT as a moving  \n25:particle that updates its state based on the Gamma Ray (GR) observations and    \n26:spatial constraints, we can create incredibly strong baseline predictions to    \n27:feed into our Gradient Boosting models.                                         \n28-\n29-\n30:                 2. The Spatial Reality (Geology is Continuous)                 \n31-\n32-A well doesn't exist in a vacuum; it shares the same geological formation as its\n33:neighbors.                                                                      \n34-\n35-Relying solely on X and Y coordinates in a tree model is inefficient. A better  \n36:approach is using Spatial Imputation (like cKDTree) to find the nearest known   \n37:wells and calculate the median TVT or formation depth in that specific localized\n38-area.                                                                           \n39-\n40:Feeding this \"spatial neighborhood consensus\" as a feature massively stabilizes \n41-the predictions for unseen evaluation rows.                                     \n--\n43-By shifting the focus from \"tuning model hyperparameters\" to \"building          \n44:physics-aware and spatial-aware features\", the performance jump is massive.     \n45-\n46:Are you guys currently using any sequential tracking (like Particle             \n47-Filters/Kalman Filters) or mostly relying on heavy rolling/lag statistical      \n--\n54-hengck23 ▲11 2026-05-13\n55:Check rogii patent on its product startsteer. Its viterbi/ beam search includes \n56-using dip equation                                                              \n57:US20190106974A1 — “Systems and methods for horizontal well geosteering”         \n58:US20230019126A1 — “Methods for Assisted and Automated Horizontal Well           \n59-Geosteering”                                                                    \n60-\n61: • select big segment size.                                                     \n62- • select dip range.                                                            \n--\n67- • select best algorithm / best K-value.                                        \n68: • repeat over segment sizes and dip ranges.                                    \n69-\n70-                                                                                \n71: for segment_size in choices:                                                   \n72-     for dip_model in choices:                                                  \n73-         for algorithm in choices:                                              \n74:             project lateral log into TVT                                       \n75:             compare with typewell log                                          \n76:             score by similarity K                                              \n77- choose best-scoring interpretation                                             \n--\n84-\n85:faizan ▲1 2026-05-14\n86-Really well-articulated post, and I think you've put your finger on something a \n--\n88-about sequential context is especially underrated. Most people's first instinct \n89:with lag features is a fixed rolling window (last 3–5 rows of GR or MD delta),  \n90:but that's essentially a flat prior — it treats all neighbors equally regardless\n91:of geological consistency. A Kalman Filter or even a lightweight Particle Filter\n92-changes that entirely by letting the model track state and weight recent        \n93:observations by how well they fit the expected trajectory. The signal quality   \n94:improvement on noisy GR readings alone makes it worth the implementation effort.\n95:On the spatial imputation side, I've had good results with a similar cKDTree    \n96-approach, but one thing worth experimenting with is distance-weighted           \n--\n99-your search radius. Also, if the competition data has any formation labels or   \n100:lithology markers, conditioning the spatial neighborhood on those (rather than  \n101-raw Euclidean XY distance) tends to produce much cleaner consensus features. One\n102:thing I'd add to your framework: azimuth and inclination derived from the       \n103:trajectory (X, Y, Z, MD) can be reconstructed and used to estimate the          \n104:wellbore's entry angle into each formation. That angular context, combined with \n105:your spatial neighborhood TVT, gives the gradient boosting model a much richer  \n106-\"where am I and where am I headed\" signal rather than just \"what are the raw    \n107:coordinates.\" Fully agree that hyperparameter chasing on a feature-poor dataset \n108-has heavily diminishing returns. The ceiling you're describing is real — the    \n109:delta comes from feature engineering, not from squeezing one more tree out of   \n110-XGBoost.                                                                        \n--\n114-）而不是平坦的中值和mdash;”这一观点十分赞同，但我还有一个小小的疑问，我该怎么寻 \n115:找附近的井？是根据每个样本的xyz值吗？这样的话是不是要将train中所有的样本数据综合\n116-起来分析？                                                                      \n--\n119-Really good point. I think many people are treating this as a pure tabular      \n120:problem while the data is clearly sequential + spatial. The idea of combining   \n121:trajectory-aware features with spatial neighborhood information makes a lot of  \n122:sense, especially for stabilizing predictions across nearby wells.              \n123-\n\\n### discussion_699326.md\n1:╭─ stage.1 : global search using linear prior tvt = linear(md,z) ──────────────╮\n2-│ Author: hengck23 | Votes: 18 | Comments: 5 | Created: 2026-05-13             │\n3:│ https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discus │\n4-│ sion/699326                                                                  │\n--\n10-\n11:Next post: stage.2 iterative local search for refinement                        \n12-\n--\n19-\n20:initalise with fitted line of md,z after PS and also using tvt_input. need to   \n21-think of  a way to make it \"smooth\"                                             \n--\n35-\n36:top to bottom: typewell TVT-GR after PS, typewell TVT-GS, horizontal            \n37:MD-smoothedGS showing forward and reverse, horizontal MD-smoothedGS showing TVT \n38:as color, horizontal TVT-smoothedGS                                             \n39-\n--\n49-\n50:lower GR fitting doesn't mean lower T ** it is an inverse problem ! **          \n51-\n52:You should learn the 2-parameter prior space using TVT RMSE, not GR RMSE.       \n53-\n\\n### discussion_698002.md\n1:╭─ Is online learning / test-time fine-tuning allowed? ────────────────────────╮\n2-│ Author: Kh0a | Votes: 17 | Comments: 5 | Created: 2026-05-08                 │\n3:│ https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discus │\n4-│ sion/698002                                                                  │\n--\n7-With the current evaluation setup, participants can train the model offline and \n8:then fine-tune it using the test dataset at submission time by peeking at the   \n9:actual test dataset. They can only extract the available TVT_input (calibration \n10-reference) and other features but can make a solid improvement through domain   \n--\n14-\n15: 1 Load the hidden test data (wellbores + GR, formation parameters, TVT_input)  \n16: 2 Fine-tune t