                  │\n3:│ https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discus │\n4-│ sion/704273                                                                  │\n--\n9-I'm relatively new to this competition, but it seems there's some distribution  \n10:shift between train and test. My local CV and public RMSE diverge by up to 2 in \n11:some cases. On top of that, which one is more optimistic (local vs. public)     \n12-varies depending on the prediction approach. Methods that rely on specific      \n13:assumptions or modeling tend to show a larger gap. In my case, a spatial method \n14:using offset wells gives CV < LB (public is more pessimistic), while the        \n15:particle filter approach that's been popular in recent notebooks gives CV > LB  \n16:(public is more optimistic).  My thinking is that since the training set has 773\n17:wells and the public test set only has 52, we should trust local CV over the LB,\n18-assuming our validation strategy is sound.  What do you all think?              \n--\n22-Ulrich G. ▲1 2026-06-04\n23:I think we could trust, for the time being there is a line-up between CV and LB \n24-for me                                                                          \n--\n27-In my opinion, both are important. I think that leaderboard probing is a real   \n28:risk here, and your comment of trusting local CV therefore has some merit,      \n29:however, dataleaks are of critical importance. I think an honest take would be  \n30:to consider estimated confidence scores based on the population size of the test\n31:set. I.e., determine the confidence of the local CV being similar or different  \n32:to the LB score with something like a null hypothesis test. This may help to    \n33:determine if the lb score is true or fake, but requires honest engineering of   \n34-the model too.                                                                  \n--\n38-寿! ▲1 2026-06-04\n39:That makes sense. I also feel like there tends to be a trend where LB improves  \n40:when CV improves, though the ranges seem to be on different scales.             \n41-\n42-寿! ▲1 2026-06-04\n43:Thank you for the insightful advice! You're right that a statistically-grounded \n44-approach seems to be key here.                                                  \n--\n46-Tucker Arrants 2026-06-04\n47:Yes, when I make larger pipeline changes, my CV-LB correlation \"resets\" but then\n48:any CV improvements with small tuning within that new pipeline always lead to LB\n49-improvements.                                                                   \n50-\n51:Perhaps has to do the \"harder\" training wells that massively hurt CV, so        \n52-improvements on the hard wells at the cost of performance on the easy wells can \n53:result in better CV but not necessarily translate to LB (perhaps because public \n54:LB has many \"easy\" wells but these are all relative terms to your model).       \n55-\n\\n### discussion_701034.md\n1:╭─ Surface columns (ANCC, ASTNU, etc.) are in TVD (Z), NOT in TVT ─────────────╮\n2-│ Author: Nicolas Bridelance | Votes: 9 | Comments: 2 | Created: 2026-05-18    │\n3:│ https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discus │\n4-│ sion/701034                                                                  │\n--\n8-\n9:I spent some time debugging a visualization issue that might trip up someone    \n10-somewhere, so sharing it here.                                                  \n--\n13-\n14:The six geological surface columns in the horizontal well files:                \n15-\n--\n17-\n18:are stored as negative TVD values (same unit as the Z column, typically ranging \n19:from -9500 to -7500 ft), not in TVT.                                            \n20-\n21:If you try to plot them directly against TVT (which ranges from ~11000 to 12000 \n22-ft), they'll appear completely off-scale and useless.                           \n--\n25-\n26:Map each surface value from Z-space to TVT-space using the well's own Z→TVT     \n27:relationship. Since Z and TVT are almost perfectly correlated (|r| ≈ 0.999), a  \n28-simple linear interpolation works well:                                         \n--\n32-                                                                                \n33: hw_clean = hw.dropna(subset=['Z', 'TVT']).sort_values('Z')                     \n34: z_to_tvt = interp1d(hw_clean['Z'].values, hw_clean['TVT'].values,              \n35-                     kind='linear', bounds_error=False, fill_value='extrapolate \n36-                                                                                \n37: surface_tvt = float(z_to_tvt(hw['ANCC'].dropna().iloc[0]))                     \n38-                                                                                \n39-\n40:Why it matters for modeling Using raw Z values as if they were TVT will         \n41:introduce an error of ~20,000 ft (the offset between negative TVD and positive  \n42:TVT).                                                                           \n43-\n--\n47-\n48:shanzhong8 2026-05-19\n49:Does this preprocessing strategy result in information leakage?                 \n50-\n51-Nicolas Bridelance 2026-05-21\n52:Good question. The mapping doesn't introduce leakage because:                   \n53-\n54:Z (TVD) is fully provided for all wells including test — it's the borehole      \n55:trajectory, independent of the TVT target The interpolator uses Z ↔ TVT_input   \n56:pairs from the known (non-masked) portion of the well The geological surface    \n57-depths (ANCC etc.) are formation tops in the vertical section, well within the  \n58:range covered by TVT_input The transformation is purely geometric (coordinate   \n59:conversion), not predictive. The TVT values you're actually predicting are at   \n60:intermediate MD positions along the lateral, not at the surface depths.         \n61-\n\\n### discussion_702919.md\n1:╭─ Dynamic Programming for TVT Tracking: What Worked, What Didn't, and What th─╮\n2-│ Author: Matteo Niccoli | Votes: 5 | Comments: 0 | Created: 2026-05-27        │\n3:│ https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discus │\n4-│ sion/702919                                                                  │\n--\n11-\n12:Dynamic Programming for TVT Tracking: What Worked, What Didn't, and What the Gap\n13-Tells Us                                                                        \n--\n16-Following up on my earlier discussion on domain priors, I tried a different     \n17:approach to TVT tracking: dynamic programming (DP).                             \n18-\n19-The idea in plain terms: The bit traces a physical path through the formation.  \n20:TVT at one position constrains what TVT can be at the next position; it can't   \n21:jump 50 ft in one sample. Most trackers in this competition (particle filters,  \n22:beam search) use heuristics to exploit this constraint. DP is the brute-force   \n23:alternative: evaluate every possible TVT path through the typewell state space  \n24:and pick the one that best matches the observed GR log, subject to a smoothness \n25-penalty. No randomness, no pruning, guaranteed global optimum for each parameter\n26:set. The trade-off is that you discretize the state space (~400 candidate TVT   \n27-positions in a +/-200 ft window around the anchor).                             \n--\n29-I ran five configurations with different smoothness settings, from \"stiff\"      \n30:(strongly resist TVT changes between positions, producing smooth paths that     \n31:capture the broad trend) to \"loose\" (allow rapid TVT changes, producing         \n32-responsive but noisier paths that track local dip). Ensembling these gives the  \n33-model both structural trend and local sensitivity. These paths + their ensemble \n34:statistics + GR residuals at various offsets = 24-75 features fed into the same \n35-LightGBM.                                                                       \n36-\n37:For the geophysicists: this is the same algorithm as Hale's dynamic warping of  \n38-seismic images. Not conventional seed-based autotracking, but the DP-based      \n--\n41-\n42:Dynamic image warping (Hale, 2013) — find shifts u(t) that align image f to     \n43-image g:                                                                        \n--\n48-\n49:Geosteering TVT tracking (this notebook) — find TVT states that align lateral GR\n50:to typewell GR:                                                                 \n51-\n52-                                                                                \n53: min sum_i [ (GR_obs_i - GR_typewell[state_i])^2 / sigma + mu * |state_i -      \n54- state_{i-1}| ]                                                                 \n--\n56-\n57:Both minimize a data-fit term (how well the observed signal matches the         \n58:reference at the candidate position) plus a regularization term (how much the   \n59-shift or state jumps between adjacent positions). Replace \"seismic trace\" with  \n60:\"lateral GR log\", \"reference image\" with \"typewell\", \"shift\" with \"TVT state\",  \n61-and you have the same algorithm. The same DP structure appears in speech signal \n62-alignment (Sakoe and Chiba, 1978), sequence decoding (Viterbi, 1967), and       \n63:seismic image warping (Hale, 2013). All are instances of Bellman's (1962)       \n64:dynamic programming principle. Pure numpy, no Numba, deterministic, ~25 min for \n65-773 wells.                                                                      \n--\n69- • The Viterbi ensemble mean became the #1 feature by LightGBM gain importance, \n70:   ahead of all NCC and trajectory features                                     \n71- • 7 of the top 20 features are Viterbi-derived                                 \n72- • OOF improved by 0.46 total (14.806 to 14.346) across two iterations (v1:     \n73:   +0.154 from 5 Viterbi paths, v2: +0.226 from expanded GR residual families + \n74-   confidence features + 2-seed blend)                                          \n--\n77-\n78: • LB barely moved: 14.081 vs 14.082 baseline (a one-thousandth of a foot       \n79-   improvement)                                                                 \n80: • This is a textbook CV-overfitting signature: OOF improved 0.46 ft but LB     \n81-   improved 0.001 ft, while fold variance increased from 0.44 to 0.87. The      \n82:   Viterbi features fit the training distribution well but don't generalize to  \n83-   the held-out test wells                                                      \n84: • Post-processing (alpha/tau grid-searched on OOF) added only ~0.05            \n85- • Confidence features (cost gap between best and second-best Viterbi path)     \n86:   contributed near-zero gain despite being theoretically the unique advantage  \n87:   of full-state DP over beam search                                            \n88: • NCC-centered GR residual family was the least informative; anchor-centered   \n89-   was the most informative                                                     \n--\n91-The interesting tension: the model ranks Viterbi features #1 by importance but  \n92:the score barely improves on LB. This means the Viterbi paths carry signal that \n93:is partially redundant with existing NCC features. Both measure GR-typewell     \n94-similarity; the Viterbi adds sequential consistency but the observation model   \n95:(point-by-point GR comparison) is too noisy for the consistency to help much.   \n96-\n--\n98-\n99:The Viterbi architecture is correct: it keeps all states alive (unlike beam     \n100-search which prunes to 8-20) and guarantees the global optimum per parameter    \n101:set. But its observation cost is crude. A single GR value is a weak             \n102:discriminator between adjacent TVT positions. Independent validation from       \n103:sleep3r's shuffled-GR experiment: their normal-GR top-10 heatmap coverage was   \n104:essentially indistinguishable from shuffled GR (the shuffled version actually   \n105:scored marginally higher, which is the noise floor). Point-by-point GR matching \n106-operates in the noise regime.                                                   \n--\n109-pattern I see is that the leading solutions compensate not with better decoders,\n110:but with a fundamentally different signal source: spatial structural information\n111:from neighboring wells. The ~5 ft gap between ~14 and ~9 RMSE appears to be not \n112:about more features or better inference over the GR-typewell match, but about   \n113-adding a second, independent information channel.                               \n--\n117-\n118:We tested the naive prediction TVT = -Z + C (flat formation assumption). In the \n119:lateral section: 55 ft RMSE. Per-well correlation between dTVT and -dZ          \n120-increments: median r = 0.79 (r-squared = 0.62).                                 \n--\n122-These are consistent, not contradictory. The r = 0.79 measures increment        \n123:direction correlation: when Z goes down, TVT usually goes up, and vice versa.   \n124:But the within-lateral dTVT/dZ slope is ~+0.057, not the -1 that the naive model\n125:assumes. Z wiggles ~14x more than TVT in the lateral because the bit is drilling\n126:roughly horizontal through a nearly flat formation. High directional correlation\n127:+ near-zero slope + large cumulative drift coexist: the naive model accumulates \n128:a growing error despite \"predicting the right direction\" 62% of the time. Our GR\n129-matching reduces 55 to 14.3 ft by capturing the actual formation dip; the       \n130:remaining gap to sub-10 requires spatial structure from neighboring wells.      \n131-\n132:A cautionary tale - GR scaling:                                                 \n133-\n134-The first run produced completely flat paths (path_range = 0.0 for all five     \n135:configs). Root cause: clean_gr() z-scores the GR, shrinking values to [-3, 3].  \n136:With z-scored GR, the observation cost was ~0.03/position while movement costs  \n137:were 4-35. The DP never justified leaving the anchor. Fix: raw GR in API units  \n138:for the Viterbi cost function, while NCC features continue using z-scored GR    \n139:upstream. If you're building a physics-based cost function on top of normalized \n140-features, check the scaling.                                                    \n--\n145-\n146: • Seismic image warping: Hale (2013) - \"dynamic warping\"; Yan and Wu (2021) -  \n147:   \"DP-based horizon extraction\"                                                \n148: • Speech recognition: Sakoe and Chiba (1978) - \"dynamic time warping\"          \n149- • Communications: Viterbi (1967) - \"Viterbi algorithm\"                         \n150- • Bioinformatics: gene structure decoding - \"HMM decoding\"                     \n151: • Automated geosteering: Zeng, Bhaidasna, and Zou (IADC/SPE-230729-MS, 2026) - \n152:   particle filter + DTW, validating the log-correlation approach in a          \n153-   commercial context                                                           \n154-\n155:The geoscience community knows this as \"dynamic warping\" or \"DP-based horizon   \n156-extraction\"; the signal processing community calls it the \"Viterbi algorithm.\"  \n157:Four-phase structure is identical: initialize, forward-accumulate, minimize     \n158-terminal state, backtrack.                                                      \n--\n162-The DP discussion above covers the sequential tracker side of the problem. But  \n163:from reviewing the top-scoring public notebooks in this competition             \n164:(particularly the v43 spatial-pooling notebook and the inference-stack          \n165:notebook), I see a second pattern at work: a smooth regional surface provides a \n166-structural backbone, and local signal matching corrects the residual.           \n--\n168-In seismic interpretation, Gogia et al. (2020, Interpretation/SEG-dGB) built a  \n169:hybrid horizon tracker that combines inversion-based dip flattening (a smooth   \n170:surface fitted to the regional dip field) with similarity-based autotracking    \n171:(local event correlation that snaps the surface to the correct reflector).      \n172:Without the autotracker, the dip-only surface drifts off-phase; without the dip \n173:surface, the autotracker creates holes and loop-skips. The hybrid outperforms   \n174-either component alone.                                                         \n175-\n176:The same decomposition appears in this competition. The spatial structural      \n177:backbone (formation plane fits from neighboring wells, implemented as           \n178:FormationPlaneKNN in the top-scoring public notebooks) is the dip-flattening    \n179:analog: a smooth regional surface that predicts TVT from spatial position alone.\n180:GR-typewell matching (NCC, Viterbi, particle filters) is the autotracker analog:\n181:it locks the prediction to the correct stratigraphic position using the local   \n182-log signature. Neither alone reaches sub-10; the combination does.              \n--\n186-lacked the structural guide. The top-scoring notebooks I reviewed have both. The\n187:lesson generalizes: in any tracking problem where a smooth prior surface exists \n188-and local observations are noisy, the hybrid architecture (structural guide +   \n--\n192-\n193: • Hale, D. (2013). Dynamic warping of seismic images. Geophysics, 78(2),       \n194-   S105-S115.                                                                   \n195: • Yan, S. and Wu, X. (2021). Seismic horizon extraction with dynamic           \n196:   programming. Geophysics, 86(2), IM51-IM62.                                   \n197: • Sakoe, H. and Chiba, S. (1978). Dynamic programming algorithm optimization   \n198-   for spoken word recognition. IEEE Trans. ASSP, 26, 43-49.                    \n199: • Gogia, R., Singh, R., de Groot, P., et al. (2020). Tracking 3D seismic       \n200:   horizons with a new hybrid tracking algorithm. Interpretation, 8(4), 1-7.    \n201: • Zeng, Y., Bhaidasna, K., and Zou, A. (2026). IADC/SPE-230729-MS.             \n202-\n\\n### discussion_698825.md\n2-│ Author: Igor Kuvaev | Votes: 51 | Comments: 3 | Created: 2026-05-11          │\n3:│ https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discus │\n4-│ sion/698825                                                                  │\n--\n6-\n7:Kagglers, you are doing great so far, and we are excited to see the improving   \n8:RMSE on the leaderboard. In the comments on this post, I will share some helpful\n9-tricks that geologists use to come up with the best interpretations.            \n--\n13-Igor Kuvaev ▲3 2026-05-11\n14:GR from the lateral before the Prediction Start point has better resolution than\n15:the GR from the type well.                                                      \n16-\n17:If the well is going in the negative direction in the TVT domain from the       \n18:Prediction Start point, then the correlation with the GR from the lateral will  \n19:be better. Therefore, it is better to use the GR from the lateral before the    \n20:Prediction Start point for the lateral GR correlation.                          \n21-\n22:In my image, the red curve correlates better with the green curve than the type \n23:well (gray).                                                                    \n24-\n25-🌆 \n26:inbox%2F31464355%2F33faa3899bb47175c4a0b2edb5eb3661%2FGR_before_PS.png?generatio\n27-n=1778525111769053&alt=media                                                    \n--\n29-Igor Kuvaev ▲5 2026-05-11\n30:Lateral Well GR correlates on itself. Lateral Well GR has better resolution than\n31:Typewell GR                                                                     \n32-\n33-🌆 \n34:inbox%2F31464355%2Ff59c00700a6b51b1fc2ab4022683a215%2FGR_correlates%20on%20itsel\n35-f.png?generation=1778527935587790&alt=media                                     \n--\n37-🌆 \n38:inbox%2F31464355%2F6b596aa59019f6963745c2d1a90c18c4%2FGR_correlates%20on%20itsel\n39-f%202.png?generation=1778527957181745&alt=media                                 \n\\n### discussion_698449.md\n1:╭─ Duplicate type wells for different horizontal wells ────────────────────────╮\n2-│ Author: RMorrison | Votes: 19 | Comments: 3 | Created: 2026-05-09            │\n3:│ https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discus │\n4-│ sion/698449                                                                  │\n--\n7-When doing a quick EDA, I noticed there are a few type well files that are      \n8:exactly the same but assigned to different horizontal wells. In some cases this \n9-makes sense (wells that are oriented adjacent or on top of each other), but in  \n--\n15-\n16:duplicate_groups = [ ['02e7fe5a', '10b89021', '3417285d', '6ae68655',           \n17-'7993a768', 'bc4381e2', 'ecdab904', 'f021b650', 'f49fdea3', 'f88ddb26'],        \n--\n30-\n31:Typically typewell selection is a manual process, the geologist picks the one   \n32-that is close to the lateral and available at the time. Wells in the project    \n33-were drilled over 10 years and when you were drilling certain lateral the       \n34:closest typewell (the one the is close now) could not be available.             \n35-\n36:Additionally the geologist may take TVT GR data from the nearby interpreted     \n37-lateral to interpret the next lateral. Sometimes this helps a lot and this      \n38:approach is called \"pseudo-typewell\". Some of the typewells in the project are  \n39:actually \"pseudo-typewells\" - interpretations from nearby laterals drilled prior\n40-to the current one.                                                             \n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
